Co7U40iTXm_rCBT9ZHUcCGT-UExmA-xvPSkEiWoUeFm8kjK9efWF4jH5jrWBy7MAmwIGrCQx56eZ1APe8jRY5gni9eddRzcANsASnNVMfhhLlyBj2ct143B0Gf1q85Ia5eKMezd3gJjNxSm4T8zXs-DbOR1OF5Jds6CK2jJGcf8CV4BvRMy_JrOGd3X6SjvxiQa7hfmBjx3vvn6yRcLAU8J4-QZ0FyB2EdHM_STrsZpIqCiddpx8SJmLYDXdbWA81KK9ZkXwctqBWqk8voqkSH9u3uCjq1CUHbQ==\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering py4j class reflection**\\\\n\\\\nI'm reflecting on py4j classes, and if there’s no metadata, the native functions might fail or produce empty results. However, adding py4j metadata could be against some guidelines. I wonder if dynamic access coverage improvements are achieved through tests executed in the JVM with an agent running first, so perhaps running tests isn't necessary. The user only asked about committing tests, not about metadata. Typically, we don’t add metadata to test helpers unless it's required.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering class and method access**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about public inner non-static classes and filtering static ones. Using `getPublicStaticClassNames` helps with that, and for `getClass`, it's all about finding by the simple name. \\\\n\\\\nMeanwhile, `getPublicFieldNames` lets me access public fields through `obj.getClass().getFields()`, and it's crucial to include metadata. I see `getPublicStaticFieldNames` operates similarly for static fields, while `getPublicMethodNames` works with `getMethods` to include methods too. There’s a lot to keep track of!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_1q5FDoGcSQTYksvUtqtMjNd8|fc_0a385e3523b47e330169f11570869c81959358c5afda1945ae\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"rg -n \\\"allPublicClasses|allDeclaredClasses|queryAll|queried\\\" . | head -100\", \"timeout\": 10}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 3500, \"output\": 1351, \"cacheRead\": 45056, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 49907, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777407321242, \"responseId\": \"resp_0a385e3523b47e330169f11559e84c8195b928c4f0be071e28\"}}\n3981:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering py4j class reflection**\\n\\nI'm reflecting on py4j classes, and if there’s no metadata, the native functions might fail or produce empty results. However, adding py4j metadata could be against some guidelines. I wonder if dynamic access coverage improvements are achieved through tests executed in the JVM with an agent running first, so perhaps running tests isn't necessary. The user only asked about committing tests, not about metadata. Typically, we don’t add metadata to test helpers unless it's required.\\n\\n**Considering class and method access**\\n\\nI’m thinking about public inner non-static classes and filtering static ones. Using `getPublicStaticClassNames` helps with that, and for `getClass`, it's all about finding by the simple name. \\n\\nMeanwhile, `getPublicFieldNames` lets me access public fields through `obj.getClass().getFields()`, and it's crucial to include metadata. I see `getPublicStaticFieldNames` operates similarly for static fields, while `getPublicMethodNames` works with `getMethods` to include methods too. There’s a lot to keep track of!\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0a385e3523b47e330169f1155abc9481959e4549021b0c6d9c\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp8RVwaccUDMD71WCKmo_R4C3RZubuXZq0blwTK9KgAo17h_yLXyzia6S8iM9b0Ui9IWIzXq-HHcVFzu2WlLBL4HsaIkzoSeqNR4yBM8LOM0FiUFks_jg837T0BmM0MxdJ8WO1sv_I5eY9VWQUtuPbknPBHYPVpbzZCGmZONtiCcySOLUoBDM7Lh5kJWdu5y_Eh2FIlWPyyGF87r_7rGBfmSOtDeMOfyo0tQyDjmc55C9dqXbidsYbGyaB2CmwucXC4eRrmTms_cxs0Y6DgDJLD5lfra1XcefrHU8-HxPphexN58HMnvXH_yYYmrEEJ_Lio3dZIxi-yEB4DfNlO6KZmWZkwBqe6S4sZzg7V4DgVhsitwRl4N